social_posts.post_text: My wife dresses me.

Gael needed to warm up to the big man, but just before we were about to head out, he said, “I want to sit on Santa’s lap!” So we went for round 2!!! 

This was his first opportunity to sit on St. Nick’s lap, since being born during lockdown in 2020. Definitely a special moment. Thank you Frankford Hall.
2023 check in! I hope this year is the culmination of everything you’ve been working towards. Great things are on the horizon. Manifest it! Happy new year. ♥️
Thank you for everything 1443. You’re a part of our family. The START of our family. We will miss you, dearly.

Even though our home is each other, I’ll always have a soft spot for 1443. It’s the first home we bought together and eventually became parents in. Through it all…basement floods, a broken lateral, summer ants, patio movie nights, birthday bbq’s, sleepless newborn nights and a pandemic lockdown, it was beautiful…it was our beautiful. We loved on that house and it loved us back. Letting it go was a decision made through bittersweet tears so it is my hope that the next owners, whoever they’ll be, will appreciate it as much as we did. ❤️🏠 #ThankYou

Having fun partying on that boat this MDW?!! Cool cool. ‘Cause we’re potty training. 💩 in the shower. 💩 on the back patio. 💩 everywhere but the potty. So much fun. Literally a 💩 show. 

If you’ve done this before, you know you’re pretty much confined to your home and maybe a one block radius, if you’re lucky. Thankfully we had a @lovevery play kit arrive just in time. It’s kept Gael occupied and all of us from going stir crazy. 

About this Play Kit (The Observer, months 37, 38, 39):

Welcome your new three-year-old to the "Year of the Self" as they take ownership of their routines, build emotional intelligence, and make sense of their world through open-ended play.

• Explore routines with pretend play
• Practice nesting with early exposure to architecture concepts
• Set expectations by planning their day
• Encourage independence and self care

I was flattered that I was asked to present, but shit, speaking in front of a ton of people is terrifying… especially when it’s a room full of people you respect and admire. I think I only flubbed, like, once though. @paulcubbybryant, were you keeping track??? 

The last slide is a bit of a flex, but whatever. Any interviewer is lying if they tell you that an artist complimenting your interview skills isn’t the best feeling in the world. I love the art of conversing, and softening intrusive questions to make them feel non-threatening, even warm. Interviewing is probably my favorite part of the gig, so when a celeb notices the work that goes into it, hell yeah it feels good!

It’s giving Canal Street Adam Levine 💀

What a night. The tri-state welcomed @WeCanSurvive to the east coast with open arms — a SOLD OUT @PruCenter!!! Seeing this all come to life after months and months of preparation was so gratifying. And seeing our NYC team in action?! My co-workers are the best in the biz. Period. I’m blessed to work alongside them.

S/O to our partner over at @AFSPnational. Mental health awareness took center stage last night, and I was honored to be a small piece of puzzle. 

Also, in the final video, if you listen closely, you can hear a hilarious exchange between myself and our listeners. I walked on stage and the crowd ERUPTED! Now, I know a few people enjoy my radio show, but that response was suspicious. I immediately put it together… “Oh, no, no. I’m not Adam Levine. Sit down, please. I’m sorry.” 😆🤷🏻‍♂️
